s attributionsharealike license additional terms may apply by using this site you agree to the terms of use and privacy policy wikipedia® is a registered trademark of the wikimedia foundation inc a nonprofit organization privacy policy about wikipedia disclaimers contact wikipedia developers cookie statement mobile view barclays  wikipedia barclays from wikipedia the free encyclopedia jump to navigation search this article is about the british banking firm for items that may be pluralised as barclays see barclay disambiguation barclays plc type public limited company traded as lse barc nyse bcs ftse  component industry banking financial services founded  november   years ago  in london kingdom of england headquarters london e united kingdom area served worldwide key people john mcfarlane chairman jes staley group chief executive products retail banking commercial banking investment banking investment management revenue £ billion  operating income £ billion  profit £ billion  total assets £ trillion  total equity £ billion  number of employees   divisions barclaycard barclays investment bank barclays wealth subsidiaries barclays africa group barclays bank website wwwhomebarclays wwwarchivebarclayscom barclays ˈbɑːrkliz is a british multinational bank and financial services company headquartered in london it is a universal bank with operations in retail wholesale and investment banking as well as wealth management mortgage lending and credit cards it has operations in over  countries and territories and has around  million customers barclays is organised into four core businesses personal  corporate personal banking corporate banking wealth  investment management barclaycard investment banking and africa barclays traces its origins to a goldsmith banking business established in the city of london in  james barclay became a partner in the business in  in  several banks in london and the english provinces including backhouses bank and gurneys bank united as a jointstock bank under the name barclays and co over the following decades barclays expanded to become a nationwide bank in  barclays deployed the worlds first cash dispenser barclays has made numerous corporate acquisitions including of london provincial and south western bank in  british linen bank in  mercantile credit in  the woolwich in  and the north american operations of lehman brothers in  barclays has a primary listing on the london stock exchange and is a constituent of the ftse  index it has a secondary listing on the new york stock exchange according to a  paper by vitali et al barclays was the most powerful transnational corporation in terms of ownership and thus corporate control over global financial stability and market competition with axa and state street corporation taking the nd and rd position respectively contents  history   to    to    to    to   st century  abandoned merger with abn amro  financing  lehman brothers acquisition   to present  operations  principal divisions and subsidiaries  branches and atms  senior management  executive committee  board of directors  sponsorships  controversies  involvement with south africa under apartheid  financial support for the government in zimbabwe  accusations of money laundering  senior management bonuses  tax avoidance   tax repayment  conflicts of interest  customer satisfaction  ratefixing scandal  staff diversity  qatari capital raising regulatory investigations  us electricity market manipulation  gold price manipulation  us lawsuit alleging dark pool fraud  exchangerate rigging last look system  unsuitable mutual fund transactions  bibliography  see also  notes  references  external links historyedit  to edit barclays traces its origins back to  when john freame a quaker and thomas gould started trading as goldsmith bankers in lombard street london the name barclays became associated with the business in  when james barclay the soninlaw of john freame one of the founders became a partner in the business in  the bank moved to  lombard street identified by the sign of the black spread eagle which in subsequent years would become a core part of the banks visual identity much of the wealth of the barclay family was founded on the slave trade david and alexander barclay were engaged in the slave trade in  david barclay owned a great plantation in jamaica later freeing his slaves and coming to appreciate their equivalence to whites in  the firm was styled barclay bevan and bening and so remained until  when another partner john tritton who had married a barclay was admitted and the business then became barclay bevan bening and tritton in  several banks in london and the english provinces notably backhouses bank of darlington and gurneys bank of norwich united under the banner of barclays and co a jointstock bank  to edit the barclays bank branch in sutton london which was originally a branch of london and provincial prior to acquisition by barclays between  and  barclays extended its branch network by making acquisitions of small english banks further expansion followed in  when barclays amalgamated with the london provincial and south western bank and in  when the british linen bank was acquired by barclays bank although the british linen bank retained a separate board of directors and continued to issue its own bank notes see banknotes of the pound sterling in  the colonial bank national bank of south africa and the angloegyptian bank were amalgamated and barclays operated its overseas operations under the name barclays bank dominion colonial and overseas – barclays dco in  barclays acquired the first indian exchange bank the central exchange bank of india which had opened in london in  with the sponsorship of central bank of india  to edit in may  barclays was the first uk bank to appoint a female bank manager hilda harding managed barclays hanover square branch in london until her retirement in  a plaque in enfield united kingdom commemorating the installation of th